[2]
Date: Mon, 27 Nov 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Korea Herald [edited]
<http://www.koreaherald.co.kr/SITE/data/html_dir/2006/11/27/200611270060.asp>

A 2nd [in light of the previous item, this one becomes 3rd. - Mod.AS]
outbreak of bird flu has been detected in Seosan, about 140 km north
of Iksan where the fatal H5N1 led to a massive culling of poultry and
other animals.[Seosan is located at Lat 36.7817, Long 126.4522, map
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/KS/17/Sosan.html>].
Provincial officials said the sick chickens were hatched from eggs
distributed in mid-November from a breeding farm in Iksan, North
Jeolla Province. But the authorities have not yet confirmed whether
the Seosan chickens were infected with the highly virulent strain.
"Preliminary tests indicate the virus is a harmless strain," the
Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry said in a statement.
To prevent the spread of the virus, quarantine officials have so far
destroyed about 100 000 chickens and ducks within a 500-meter radius
of Iksan, which is about 250 km south of Seoul. Officials confirmed
the H5N1 virus in the Iksan poultry on Saturday [25 Nov 2006].
The ministry said the government plans to cull a total of 236 000
birds, in addition to other animals such as pigs, dogs and cats in
the area by Thursday. About 6 million eggs will also be destroyed.
Seosan officials said they are waiting for the preliminary test
results of chickens from 8 farms in the area. They said measures have
been put in place to contain the transfer of livestock. Five of the
farms have bought livestock from breeding farms in Iksan, the
authorities said.
The latest bird flu case in Seosan is expected to unnerve
poultry-related industries. Since news of the 1st outbreak on 22 Nov
2006, major retailers have been seeing chicken sales decline.
Demand for poultry at E-Mart, the nation's largest discount store
chain, has also been declining compared to a year ago, however, at a
slower pace.
"Sales have climbed 55 percent from Thursday to Saturday compared to
a year ago, but the growth rate is slowing down," said Park Soo-beom,
a spokesman for Shinsegae Co.'s E-Mart. "We expect sales to slow
further if there continues to be reports of the bird flu spreading
because consumers would feel more uneasy," he added.
Hallim Co., the nation's No. 1 supplier of chicken and poultry
products, suffered a 30 percent drop in sales from Thursday to
Monday. Hallim commands about 25 percent of the nation's chicken
[production] market.
"The sales decline is slower compared to the first scare the nation
experienced in 2003," said Kim Dae-sik, the spokesman for Hallim.
"But we attribute this slower pace to consumers' wider awareness of
the avian influenza and how consuming chicken, if well cooked, is not
harmful to humans."
Experts assure the public that poultry is safe to consume when it is
cooked at temperatures above 75 degrees Celsius for more than 5
minutes [meaning: after the flesh has reached and maintained the
temperature of 75 C/167 F for 5 minutes at the end of cooking time;
obviously simply cooking chicken for 5 min at 167 F won't get the job
done - CopyEd.PG].
[Byline: Soh-jung]
